{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a9f5a44c-16a4-420e-bd01-fd5784e21aba","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n### 1. Recursive Wildcard Glob (`**\\*.*`) — **High Impact**\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThis walks the **entire directory tree** on every evaluation. As the repo grows, this becomes progressively slower. MSBuild must stat every file to resolve the glob. Prefer explicit file lists or narrower patterns (e.g., `**\\*.txt`).\n\n### 2. File I/O via Property Function — **Medium Impact**\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nCalling `System.IO.File.ReadAllText` during evaluation performs **disk I/O inside the evaluator**, which blocks evaluation and cannot be cached. Move this to a target that runs at build time instead.\n\n### 3. Deeply Chained `<Import>` Files — **Low-Medium Impact**\n```\ncsproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nThree levels of nested imports. Each import requires a file open, parse, and merge into the evaluation context. In this small example the cost is modest, but the pattern doesn't scale well — if more layers or conditional imports are added, evaluation time grows linearly.\n\n### Recommendations\n| Issue | Fix |\n|---|---|\n| `**\\*.*` glob | Narrow the pattern or list files explicitly |\n| `ReadAllText` property function | Move to a `<Target>` with `ReadLinesFromFile` or a custom task |\n| Nested imports | Flatten into fewer files where possible |\n\nThe recursive glob is the biggest offender — it's the only item whose cost scales with repository size.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"64b80c04-9226-4ff2-8675-66cf9d634bd1","outputTokens":430},"id":"293c090c-89cb-4276-835a-e9b6c02a51ff","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:07:33.009Z","parentId":"e19a683c-6aab-481a-ba73-4f354ea31f00"}
